Sleep_Project

2024-11-17

Description: This dataset primarily investigates sleep disorders. It collects basic information from over 300 people, including gender, age, and BMI. Additionally, it gathers basic information on factors that might affect sleep health, such as sleep duration, exercise levels, and stress levels.

Analysis objectives: Perform an exploratory analysis to uncover potential associations between lifestyle factors and sleep disorders. The report will include comprehensive data cleaning steps, descriptive statistics, and predictive models to identify significant predictors of sleep disorders, offering insights into improving sleep health.

DATA ANALYSIS

1-Heatmap of independent variables

knitr::include_graphics(
  here::here("output/heatmap.png")
)

There is a strong positive correlation (0.77) between daily steps and physical activity level. This suggests that as the number of daily steps increases, the physical activity level also tends to increase.

Also, a strong negative correlation of -0.81 between stress level and sleep duration indicates that as stress levels increase, the amount of sleep a person gets tends to decrease significantly. Similarly, the correlation of -0.90 between stress level and quality of sleep represents an even stronger negative relationship. This indicates that higher stress levels are associated with poorer quality of sleep.

Therefore, in further analyses, focusing on Daily Steps and Stress Level will provide valuable insights into their impacts on health outcomes, particularly in relation to sleep.

2-Pie chart for Sleep Disorder

knitr::include_graphics(
  here::here("output/piechart.png")
)

The pie chart displays the distribution of different sleep disorders in the dataset. This distribution shows that while most participants (58.56%) do not suffer from sleep disorders, insomnia (20.59%) and sleep apnea (20.86%) each affect roughly one-fifth of the dataset.

Daily_Steps -0.0000334 -0.5137697 0.607 No

The table summarizes the results of a univariate logistic regression analysis. Significant predictors of Sleep Disorder Status include Gender, Age, Stress Level, BMI Category, Systolic Pressure, Diastolic Pressure, and Heart Rate, all with p-values less than 0.001, indicating strong associations with sleep disorders. In contrast, Daily Steps shows no significant effect (p = 0.607), suggesting that the number of daily steps taken does not impact sleep disorder status in this analysis.

This suggests that the Random Forest model is slightly more effective in correctly classifying instances of sleep disorders compared to the SVM model.
